WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:02.534
Let's actually build something.

2
00:00:02.534 --> 00:00:08.638
I gave Claude Code a fresh project and one instruction: build a task tracker, on MetaObjects.

3
00:00:10.038 --> 00:00:19.160
By the end, you'll have this — a working API serving real data from a typed stack: database schema, Zod validation, and CRUD routes.

4
00:00:19.160 --> 00:00:21.165
All generated from one model.

5
00:00:21.165 --> 00:00:23.100
Here's how, start to finish.

6
00:00:24.500 --> 00:00:31.604
First, what we're building — a task tracker: projects, and tasks with a status and a due date.

7
00:00:31.604 --> 00:00:35.987
All you need is Node and one package, the MetaObjects CLI.

8
00:00:35.987 --> 00:00:38.556
Everything else, Claude Code does.

9
00:00:39.956 --> 00:00:42.605
No models, no setup — just the ask.

10
00:00:42.605 --> 00:00:45.253
Here's how the build actually goes.

11
00:00:46.653 --> 00:00:48.328
Step one is always meta init.

12
00:00:48.328 --> 00:00:56.937
It scaffolds your model directory, your config, and the code generators themselves — plain TypeScript, copied into your repo for you to own and edit.

13
00:00:56.937 --> 00:00:59.363
But it does something more important, too.

14
00:01:00.763 --> 00:01:04.691
It drops six skills and an AGENTS file right into your repo.

15
00:01:04.691 --> 00:01:12.286
Your agent now knows the MetaObjects workflow — author the model, generate, verify — before it writes a single line.

16
00:01:12.286 --> 00:01:14.512
You're not teaching it a new tool.

17
00:01:14.512 --> 00:01:16.280
Meta init already did that.

18
00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:20.564
So Claude writes the model — one readable file.

19
00:01:20.564 --> 00:01:26.086
A Project, a Task with a status and a due date, the relationship between them, and a grid.

20
00:01:26.086 --> 00:01:32.160
And notice the validators sitting right on the fields — child metadata that travels with the model.

21
00:01:32.160 --> 00:01:34.247
That's the entire source of truth.

22
00:01:35.647 --> 00:01:36.883
Then, meta gen.

23
00:01:36.883 --> 00:01:39.684
From those few lines: seven files.

24
00:01:39.684 --> 00:01:46.275
Your database schema, validation, and a full CRUD API — none of it hand-written.

25
00:01:47.675 --> 00:01:51.231
And it's real, idiomatic code — Drizzle and Zod here.

26
00:01:51.231 --> 00:01:54.653
Not boilerplate you babysit; output you regenerate.

27
00:01:54.653 --> 00:01:58.545
Hand-edit a file and a three-way merge keeps your changes.

28
00:01:59.945 --> 00:02:06.871
Wire it to a database and boot it, and it's a working app — the generated routes serving real task data over HTTP.

29
00:02:08.271 --> 00:02:11.569
The filters are generated and enforced from the model, too.

30
00:02:11.569 --> 00:02:14.197
Filterable fields work; anything else is a 400.

31
00:02:14.197 --> 00:02:15.707
No hand-written validation.

32
00:02:17.107 --> 00:02:18.677
Now the part that matters.

33
00:02:18.677 --> 00:02:22.723
To test the guarantee, an AI renamed a field in the generated code.

34
00:02:22.723 --> 00:02:25.985
One meta verify caught it — exit one, the build fails.

35
00:02:25.985 --> 00:02:29.669
Even with an agent writing the code, it can't silently drift.

36
00:02:31.069 --> 00:02:34.212
So I asked Claude how much this actually saved.

37
00:02:34.212 --> 00:02:43.108
Twenty-some lines of model became over two hundred lines of consistent, typed stack — two tables, validation, and ten REST endpoints.

38
00:02:43.108 --> 00:02:45.783
I hand-wrote about thirty lines of glue.

39
00:02:45.783 --> 00:02:49.060
And the one time an AI drifted, verify caught it.

40
00:02:49.060 --> 00:02:52.270
The model is the asset; the code is regenerable.

41
00:02:53.670 --> 00:02:55.293
That's getting started.

42
00:02:55.293 --> 00:02:59.878
Install the CLI, run meta init, and your agent already knows how.

43
00:02:59.878 --> 00:03:02.417
Everything's at metaobjects dot dev.

44
00:03:02.417 --> 00:03:03.828
Thanks for watching.

